│ Issue\n\nThe compiler is crashing with a `SIGSEGV` while running the `loop-vectorize`      │
│ pass. The extremely deep and repetitive stack trace is a dead giveaway for an infinite     │
│ recursion. The crash itself is a symptom of stack exhaustion.\n\nThe recursion happens     │
│ within the `LoopVectorizationCostModel` as it tries to determine which values are          │
│ loop-invariant and can be hoisted out of the loop. Specifically, the function              │
│ `shouldConsiderInvariant` calls itself on the operands of an instruction to see if they    │
│ too are invariant.\n\n### 2. Analyzing `opt`'s Log\n\nThe provided IR has a peculiar       │
│ reduction:\n\n```llvm\n%red = phi i32 [ %start, %entry ], [ %red.next, %loop ]\n%red.next  │
│ = add i32 0, %red\n```\n\nThe instruction `%red.next = add i32 0, %red` is a no-op;        │
│ `%red.next` is functionally identical to `%red`. This creates a direct cycle in the        │
│ dataflow graph: `%red` depends on `%red.next`, which in turn depends on `%red`.\n\nThe     │
│ `scalar-evolution` analysis correctly identifies `%red` and `%red.next` as loop-invariant, │
│ having the value `%start` throughout the loop. This is correct because the `add i32 0,     │
│ %red` doesn't actually change the value.\n\nHowever, the `loop-vectorize` pass's cost      │
│ model isn't quite as clever. When it analyzes `%red.next`, it sees an `add` instruction    │
│ inside the loop. To determine if `%red.next` is invariant, it checks its operands. One     │
│ operand is `0` (invariant), and the other is `%red`. It then recursively calls             │
│ `shouldConsiderInvariant` on `%red`.\n\nWhen analyzing `%red`, it sees a `phi` node. To    │
│ determine if `%red` is invariant, it checks its operands. One is `%start` (invariant), and │
│ the other is `%red.next`. It then recursively calls `shouldConsiderInvariant` on           │
│ `%red.next`.\n\nAnd there's our infinite loop: `shouldConsiderInvariant(%red.next)` ->     │
│ `shouldConsiderInvariant(%red)` -> `shouldConsiderInvariant(%red.next)`... This continues  │
│ until the stack is exhausted, leading to the crash.\n\n### 3. Root Cause Analysis\n\nThe   │
│ root cause is the mutual recursion in `shouldConsiderInvariant` when it encounters a cycle │
│ of instructions that are all considered for hoisting. The function lacks a mechanism to    │
│ detect and break this recursion, such as keeping track of the values it's currently        │
│ visiting.\n\nThe function `shouldConsiderInvariant` is defined in                          │
│ `llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/LoopVectorize.cpp`. The recursive call is:\n\n```cpp\n// In │
│ llvm::LoopVectorizationCostModel::shouldConsiderInvariant\nif (auto *I =                   │
│ dyn_cast<Instruction>(V))\n  return all_of(I->operands(), [this](Value *V) {\n    return   │
│ shouldConsiderInvariant(V) || isInvariant(V);\n  });\n```\n\nThis code iterates through an │
│ instruction's operands and recursively calls `shouldConsiderInvariant`. Without a          │
│ \"visited\" set, the cycle between `%red` and `%red.next` causes infinite                  │
│ recursion.\n\n### 4. Proposed Edit Point(s)\n\nThe fix is to add a \"visited\" set to      │
│ `shouldConsiderInvariant` to track the `Value`s currently being processed in the recursion │
│ stack. If the function is called again for a value that's already in the set, it means     │
│ we've detected a cycle. In this case, we should stop recursing and assume the value is not │
│ a candidate for hoisting (by returning `false`), which breaks the infinite loop.\n\nI will │
│ add a `DenseSet` to the `LoopVectorizationCostModel` class to serve as this visited        │
│ set.\n\n**File**: `llvm/include/llvm/Transforms/Vectorize/LoopVectorize.h`\n**Edit         │
│ Point**: Add a `DenseSet` member to the `LoopVectorizationCostModel`                       │
│ class.\n\n```cpp\nclass LoopVectorizationCostModel {\n  // ... existing members            │
│ ...\nprivate:\n  /// A set of values that are under consideration for hoisting. Used to    │
│ avoid\n  /// infinite recursion.\n  DenseSet<Value *> ValuesBeingConsidered;\n\n  // ...   │
│ existing members ...\n```\n\n**File**:                                                     │
│ `llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/LoopVectorize.cpp`\n**Edit Point**: Modify                  │
│ `shouldConsiderInvariant` to use the new `ValuesBeingConsidered` set.\n\n```cpp\nbool      │
│ LoopVectorizationCostModel::shouldConsiderInvariant(Value *V) {\n  // We are looking for   │
│ instructions that have all of their operands\n  // loop-invariant.\n  if (auto *I =        │
│ dyn_cast<Instruction>(V)) {\n    if (!ValuesBeingConsidered.insert(I).second)\n            │
│ return false;\n    bool Ret = all_of(I->operands(), [this](Value *V) {\n      return       │
│ shouldConsiderInvariant(V) || isInvariant(V);\n    });\n                                   │
│ ValuesBeingConsidered.erase(I);\n    return Ret;\n  }\n\n  return true;\n}\n```\n\nI will  │
│ replace the original implementation of `shouldConsiderInvariant` with this new version.    │
│ The logic is as follows:\n1.  When `shouldConsiderInvariant` is called for an              │
│ `Instruction`, try to insert it into `ValuesBeingConsidered`.\n2.  If the insertion fails  │
│ (i.e., the instruction is already in the set), we have found a cycle. Return `false` to    │
│ break the recursion.\n3.  If the insertion succeeds, proceed with the recursive check on   │
│ the operands.\n4.  Crucially, after the recursive calls are done for the current           │
│ instruction, remove it from the set. This is essential so that the same value can be       │
│ correctly analyzed later through a different path in the dataflow graph.\n\n### 5.         │
│ Conclusion\n\nThe crash is caused by an infinite recursion in the loop vectorizer's cost   │
│ model when analyzing a cyclic dependency in the IR. By introducing a \"visited\" set       │
│ (`ValuesBeingConsidered`), we can detect and break these cycles, preventing the stack      │
│ overflow and allowing the compiler to proceed correctly. This is a standard technique for  │
│ handling recursion on cyclic graphs and makes the analysis more robust."})                 │
